\begin_layout Section
The Determinant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}-4ac$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the discriminant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but why? Each quadratic function, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

, has two real roots, one (repeated) real root, or two complex roots.
 The discriminant discriminates between which quadratics are which.
 If the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,$
\end_inset

 of a quadratic function are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}-4ac>0$
\end_inset

, then the quadratic has two real roots (and no others).
 If the coefficients are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}-4ac=0$
\end_inset

, then the quadratic has one real root (and no others).
 If the coefficients are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}-4ac<0$
\end_inset

, then the quadratic has two complex roots (and no others).
 In this way, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}-4ac$
\end_inset

 associated with the quadratic function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 determines what type of roots 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has.
 It is determinative of the types of roots, and in this light might just
 as well be known as a determinant (which, in English, means determinative).
 In mathematics, though, that term is reserved for linear algebra.
 The determinant is a determinative calculation that can be made for any
 matrix much the same way the discriminant is a determinative calculation
 that can be made for any quadratic function.
 Exactly what the determinants determines will have to wait a short while.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The determinant of an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix is undefined if 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq n$
\end_inset

, so determinants are calculated only for 
\series bold
square matrices
\series default
, those with the same number of columns as rows.
 The determinant of a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 matrix is its lone entry.
 That is, the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
a\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 As such, the determinant is a scalar.
 The notations 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|$
\end_inset

 are used to denote the determinant of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The determinant of a square matrix with more than one row, and therefore
 more than one column, is defined recursively.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det A=(-1)^{1+1}A_{1,1}\det A_{\backslash1,1}+(-1)^{1+2}A_{1,2}\det A_{\backslash1,2}+\cdots+(-1)^{1+n}A_{1,n}\det A_{\backslash1,n}.\label{eq:determinant_row_1_expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
-12 & 49 & -45 & -10\\
28 & 45 & -46 & 23\\
-15 & -28 & 4 & -48\\
-1 & 34 & -38 & -18
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\det A=\left|\begin{array}{cccc}
-12 & 49 & -45 & -10\\
28 & 45 & -46 & 23\\
-15 & -28 & 4 & -48\\
-1 & 34 & -38 & -18
\end{array}\right|= & -12\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
45 & -46 & 23\\
-28 & 4 & -48\\
34 & -38 & -18
\end{array}\right|-49\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
28 & -46 & 23\\
-15 & 4 & -48\\
-1 & -38 & -18
\end{array}\right|\label{eq:determinant_example}\\
 & -45\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
28 & 45 & 23\\
-15 & -28 & -48\\
-1 & 34 & -18
\end{array}\right|+10\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
28 & 45 & -46\\
-15 & -28 & 4\\
-1 & 34 & -38
\end{array}\right|\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The determinant of the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrix is written in terms of the determinants of four 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrices, one application of recursive formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 To this point, the computation is not so bad.
 It would take a minute to write down this quantity by hand.
 However, you might feel no closer to the final result, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $-393,294$
\end_inset

 by the way, than before.
 Now there are four separate determinants to determine.
 To continue the computation, the determinant of each 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix would be written in terms of the determinants of three 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices, a second application of formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Thus the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 would be written in terms of twelve 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 determinants.
 A final application of formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) would yield the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in terms of twenty-four 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 determinants (scalars), at which point the arithmetic could be done and
 the determinant determined.
 If nothing else, hopefully you are convinced that completing this calculation
 by hand would take a while and be prone to error.
 The real point of this example is to familiarize yourself with the recursive
 definition.
 Making sure you get the right signs on the coefficients and extract the
 right submatrices at each step takes some practice.
 Can you use formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 4\\
-1 & 3
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:determinant"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{1+j}\det A_{\backslash1,j}$
\end_inset

 of formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are called 
\series bold
cofactors
\series default
.
 More generally, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{i+j}\det A_{\backslash i,j}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

-cofactor of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Cofactors can be computed for any row-column combination.
 Using the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

-cofactor, recursion (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be rewritten 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det A=A_{1,1}C_{1,1}+A_{1,2}C_{1,2}+\cdots+A_{1,n}C_{1,n}.
\]

\end_inset

While more succinct, this presentation hides the details of the calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $-12\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
45 & -46 & 23\\
-28 & 4 & -48\\
34 & -38 & -18
\end{array}\right|-49\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
